introduction.p:
The magnitude of the field inside is proportional to the number of turns per unit length, n and current I, and field outside zero.

	B = 
	\begin{cases}
		 \mu_0 n I, \text{ inside the solenoid.}\\
		 \\
		 0, \text{ outside the solenoid.}
	\end{cases}

For direction of the field, use Biot-Savart right hand rule on current in the coil. Thus, if axis of the solenoid is the z axis, then the direction will be either towards positive z or towards negative z.

solution.p:
(a)
				Since distance from wire is much less than the length of the wire, we can assume infinitely long wire equation applies. This gives the magnitude of the magnetic field to be

					B \amp = \dfrac{\mu_0}{2\pi}\,\dfrac{I}{s}
					 \amp = 2\times 10^{-7}\times\dfrac{10.0}{0.01} = 2\times 10^{-4}\text{ T}

sidebyside.p:
This answer can be written more compactly in terms of unit vector \hat u_\phi = \left( -\dfrac{y}{s}\, \hat u_x + \dfrac{x}{s}\, \hat u_y \right) and angles the two ends of the wire subtends at the field point P as you can see from the figure to the right.

	 \sin\,\theta_1 \amp = \dfrac{ L - z}{ \sqrt{ s^2 + (L-z)^2 }} 
	 \sin\,\theta_2 \amp = \dfrac{ z}{ \sqrt{ s^2 + (L-z)^2 }}

solution.p:
By right hand rule on each segment, we find that the fields of the four segments are all in the same direction, the direction of out-of-page. Therefore, they will all add. From symmetry, the net field will be field of one wire. The field of a single segment is for the case of a symmetric point by a finite wire as worked out in . Using the formula obtained there, the magnitude will be

	 B \amp = 4\times \dfrac{\mu_0 }{2\pi s}\, \dfrac{L/2}{ \sqrt{s^2 + L^2/4}  }
	 \amp = \dfrac{\mu_0 }{2\pi}\, \dfrac{L}{ s\,\sqrt{s^2 + L^2/4}  }

The direction is out-page.
